"content": "To find the least prime p such that n^4 + 1 is congruent to 0 modulo p^2 has a solution, we test primes p. 1. Test p=2: n^4 + 1 is congruent to 0 modulo 4. 0^4+1=1, 1^4+1=2. No solution. 2. Test p congruent to 1 modulo 8: For x^4 + 1 is congruent to 0 modulo p to have solutions, p must be 1 modulo 8. p=17: Check x^4 is congruent to -1 modulo 17. x^2 is congruent to plus or minus 4 modulo 17. If x^2 is congruent to 4, x is congruent to 2, 15 modulo 17. If x^2 is congruent to -4, x is congruent to 6, 11 modulo 17. x^4 is congruent to -1 modulo 17 implies x^8 is congruent to 1 modulo 17. Powers of 2 mod 17: 2^1=2, 2^2=4, 2^3=8, 2^4=16 is congruent to -1. So x=2 is a solution to x^4 is congruent to -1 modulo 17. The roots mod 17 are x in {2, 8, 9, 15}. Check x^4 + 1 modulo 17^2 (where 17^2 = 289): 2^4 + 1 = 17 not congruent to 0 modulo 289. 8^4 + 1 = 4097. 4097 / 289 is approximately 14.17. 9^4 + 1 = 6562. 6562 / 289 is approximately 22.7. 15^4 + 1 = 50626. 50626 / 289 is approximately 175.17. No solution for p=17. p=41: x^4 is congruent to -1 modulo 41. x^2 is congruent to plus or minus 9 modulo 41. If x^2 is congruent to 9, x is congruent to 3, 38 modulo 41. If x^2 is congruent to 32, x is congruent to 17, 24 modulo 41.",
